---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Visa Inc. (V) Intrinsic Value",
  description: "An independent intrinsic value estimate for Visa Inc. (V) using a two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF) model. Compiled by Gemini 2.5 Pro.",
  category: "study",
  published: "2026-03-18",
};

const schema = JSON.stringify({
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": meta.title,
  "description": meta.description,
  "datePublished": meta.published,
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "Gemini 2.5 Pro"
  }
});

// FINANCIAL INPUTS (in millions, from most recent FY)
const currentPrice = 302.12;
const fcf = 22928;
const cash = 15240;
const debt = 21177;
const sharesOutstanding = 2180;

// ASSUMPTIONS
const wacc = 0.085; // 8.5% Discount Rate
const growthRate1to5 = 0.12; // 12% FCF Growth Years 1-5
const terminalGrowthRate = 0.035; // 3.5% Terminal Growth

// --- DCF MATH ---

// Stage 1: Present Value of FCFs for Years 1-5
const fcfProjections = [];
let pvSumStage1 = 0;
let previousFcf = fcf;

for (let year = 1; year <= 5; year++) {
  const projectedFcf = previousFcf * (1 + growthRate1to5);
  const discountFactor = Math.pow(1 + wacc, year);
  const presentValue = projectedFcf / discountFactor;

  fcfProjections.push({
    year,
    projectedFcf,
    presentValue
  });

  pvSumStage1 += presentValue;
  previousFcf = projectedFcf;
}

// Stage 2: Terminal Value
const fcfYear6 = previousFcf * (1 + terminalGrowthRate);
const terminalValue = fcfYear6 / (wacc - terminalGrowthRate);
const pvTerminalValue = terminalValue / Math.pow(1 + wacc, 5);

// Enterprise Value & Equity Value
const enterpriseValue = pvSumStage1 + pvTerminalValue;
const equityValue = enterpriseValue + cash - debt;

// Intrinsic Value Per Share
const intrinsicValue = equityValue / sharesOutstanding;
const marginOfSafety = ((intrinsicValue - currentPrice) / intrinsicValue) * 100;

// Formatting Utilities
const formatCurrency = (val) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'currency', currency: 'USD', minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 }).format(val);
const formatMillions = (val) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style: 'decimal', maximumFractionDigits: 0 }).format(val);

const isUndervalued = currentPrice < intrinsicValue;
const verdictColor = isUndervalued ? "#4ade80" : "#f87171"; // green / red
const verdictText = isUndervalued ? "Undervalued" : "Overvalued";

// Sensitivity Matrix Data (WACC vs Terminal Growth)
const sensitivityWaccs = [0.075, 0.080, 0.085, 0.090, 0.095];
const sensitivityTgrs = [0.025, 0.030, 0.035, 0.040, 0.045];
const sensitivityMatrix = sensitivityWaccs.map(w => {
  return sensitivityTgrs.map(tgr => {
    let tempFcf = fcf;
    let tempPvSum = 0;
    for (let y = 1; y <= 5; y++) {
      tempFcf *= (1 + growthRate1to5);
      tempPvSum += tempFcf / Math.pow(1 + w, y);
    }
    const tempFcf6 = tempFcf * (1 + tgr);
    const tempTv = tempFcf6 / (w - tgr);
    const tempPvTv = tempTv / Math.pow(1 + w, 5);
    const tempEv = tempPvSum + tempPvTv;
    const tempEq = tempEv + cash - debt;
    return tempEq / sharesOutstanding;
  });
});
---
<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/visa-intrinsic-value" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-container">
    <header class="page-header">
      <h1>Visa Inc. (V) Intrinsic Value Estimate</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Compiled by Gemini 2.5 Pro</p>
      <div class="meta-info">
        <span>Published: {meta.published}</span> &bull; <span>Ticker: V</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="verdict-card">
      <div class="verdict-header" style={`border-bottom-color: ${verdictColor};`}>
        <h2>Current Valuation Verdict</h2>
        <span class="badge" style={`background-color: ${verdictColor}20; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor};`}>
          {verdictText}
        </span>
      </div>
      <div class="verdict-body">
        <div class="metric-group">
          <span class="metric-label">Current Market Price</span>
          <span class="metric-value">{formatCurrency(currentPrice)}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="metric-group highlight">
          <span class="metric-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value</span>
          <span class="metric-value" style={`color: ${verdictColor};`}>{formatCurrency(intrinsicValue)}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="metric-group">
          <span class="metric-label">Margin of Safety</span>
          <span class="metric-value">{marginOfSafety > 0 ? '+' : ''}{marginOfSafety.toFixed(2)}%</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="methodology-section">
      <h2>DCF Methodology & Rationale</h2>
      <p>This intrinsic value estimate utilizes a two-stage Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) model. Visa operates as a global payments technology company, essentially forming an oligopoly alongside Mastercard. Its business model is characterized by asset-light operations, extraordinary operating margins (typically exceeding 65%), and massive free cash flow generation. The analysis is built upon the most recent full-year financial data from StockAnalysis.com.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="assumptions-grid">
      <div class="assumption-card">
        <h3>1. FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5): {growthRate1to5 * 100}%</h3>
        <p>Visa's historical revenue and FCF growth have been incredibly resilient. As the secular shift from cash to digital payments continues globally, especially in emerging markets and B2B segments, Visa's network effects deepen. I have modeled a 12% FCF growth rate for the next 5 years. This assumes sustained transaction volume growth and continuous margin expansion driven by their highly scalable infrastructure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="assumption-card">
        <h3>2. Discount Rate (WACC): {wacc * 100}%</h3>
        <p>Using the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM) with the 10-Year US Treasury Rate at 4.18% (March 2026), a beta of roughly 0.95 (reflecting Visa's lower-than-market volatility due to recurring, essential transaction revenue), and an Equity Risk Premium of 5%, the cost of equity is calculated near 8.9%. Factoring in Visa's ultra-low debt-to-equity ratio, I arrived at a Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) of 8.5%. This is a relatively low discount rate, but entirely justified by Visa's profound economic moat and minimal default risk.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="assumption-card">
        <h3>3. Terminal Growth Rate: {(terminalGrowthRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</h3>
        <p>For the terminal stage, I have applied a 3.5% perpetual growth rate. Given global inflation targets and standard real GDP growth expectations, Visa's transaction-based revenue model inherently captures inflation (as prices rise, the percentage cut yields more nominal dollars). A 3.5% terminal rate is conservative for a business of this caliber but aligns with long-term macroeconomic realities.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="data-tables">
      <h2>Stage 1: Free Cash Flow Projections</h2>
      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Year</th>
              <th class="text-right">Projected FCF (in Millions)</th>
              <th class="text-right">Present Value (Discounted at {wacc * 100}%)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {fcfProjections.map((proj) => (
              <tr>
                <td>Year {proj.year}</td>
                <td class="text-right number-font">${formatMillions(proj.projectedFcf)}</td>
                <td class="text-right number-font">${formatMillions(proj.presentValue)}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
            <tr class="total-row">
              <td><strong>Stage 1 Total PV</strong></td>
              <td></td>
              <td class="text-right number-font"><strong>${formatMillions(pvSumStage1)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="valuation-summary">
      <h2>Valuation Summary (in Millions)</h2>
      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Present Value of FCF (Years 1-5)</td>
              <td class="text-right number-font">${formatMillions(pvSumStage1)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Terminal Value (Year 6 FCF: ${formatMillions(fcfYear6)} / ({wacc * 100}% - {(terminalGrowthRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%))</td>
              <td class="text-right number-font">${formatMillions(terminalValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Present Value of Terminal Value</td>
              <td class="text-right number-font">${formatMillions(pvTerminalValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="subtotal-row">
              <td><strong>Enterprise Value</strong></td>
              <td class="text-right number-font"><strong>${formatMillions(enterpriseValue)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Plus: Cash & Equivalents</td>
              <td class="text-right number-font">${formatMillions(cash)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Less: Total Debt</td>
              <td class="text-right number-font">-${formatMillions(debt)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="subtotal-row">
              <td><strong>Implied Equity Value</strong></td>
              <td class="text-right number-font"><strong>${formatMillions(equityValue)}</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Shares Outstanding (Diluted)</td>
              <td class="text-right number-font">{formatMillions(sharesOutstanding)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="final-row">
              <td><strong>Intrinsic Value Per Share</strong></td>
              <td class="text-right number-font" style={`color: var(--accent-color); font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700;`}>
                {formatCurrency(intrinsicValue)}
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sensitivity-matrix">
      <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
      <p>Intrinsic value is highly sensitive to the discount rate and terminal growth rate assumptions. The matrix below shows how the value per share changes under different WACC and Terminal Growth scenarios.</p>

      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table class="matrix-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th rowspan="2" colspan="2" class="matrix-label text-center" style="vertical-align: middle;">Value Per Share</th>
              <th colspan="5" class="text-center matrix-header">Terminal Growth Rate</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              {sensitivityTgrs.map(tgr => (
                <th class="text-center number-font">{(tgr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</th>
              ))}
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {sensitivityMatrix.map((row, wIndex) => (
              <tr>
                {wIndex === 0 && (
                  <th rowspan="5" class="matrix-header rotate-text">Discount Rate (WACC)</th>
                )}
                <th class="number-font text-right">{(sensitivityWaccs[wIndex] * 100).toFixed(1)}%</th>
                {row.map((val, tIndex) => {
                  const isBaseCase = wIndex === 2 && tIndex === 2;
                  return (
                    <td class={`text-center number-font ${isBaseCase ? 'base-case' : ''}`}>
                      {formatCurrency(val)}
                    </td>
                  );
                })}
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="risks-section">
      <h2>Key Risks to the Valuation</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Regulatory Pressures:</strong> Visa faces ongoing scrutiny regarding interchange fees (swipe fees). Legislation like the Credit Card Competition Act in the US could mandate routing competition, potentially pressuring margins.</li>
        <li><strong>Alternative Payment Networks:</strong> The rise of closed-loop payment systems, digital wallets cutting out card networks, or Central Bank Digital Currencies (CBDCs) could slowly erode Visa's transaction volume.</li>
        <li><strong>Macroeconomic Slowdown:</strong> Visa's revenue is heavily tied to global consumer and B2B spending. A severe global recession would immediately contract payment volumes and cross-border transactions (which carry higher margins).</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Why is Visa's discount rate (WACC) so low?</summary>
        <div class="faq-content">
          <p>Visa's WACC is modeled at 8.5% due to its incredibly low risk profile. The company essentially operates a toll-road duopoly on global commerce. Its revenues are highly diversified across geographies and deeply entrenched in the financial system. Furthermore, it carries minimal debt relative to its massive cash flows, driving down its cost of capital.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Does this DCF model account for Visa's share buybacks?</summary>
        <div class="faq-content">
          <p>Yes, indirectly. This model calculates total enterprise value based on operating free cash flows and divides it by the current diluted shares outstanding. While it doesn't dynamically model future share reductions year-by-year, the current intrinsic value calculation accurately reflects the per-share value today. If Visa continues aggressive buybacks, the intrinsic value per share will rise organically over time.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Why use a 3.5% terminal growth rate instead of the standard 2%?</summary>
        <div class="faq-content">
          <p>A standard 2% terminal rate represents mature GDP growth. However, Visa has a structural advantage: inflation. Because Visa takes a percentage cut of total transaction volume, as the cost of goods rises (inflation), Visa's revenue scales automatically without requiring additional capital expenditure. A 3.5% terminal rate better reflects long-term global real GDP growth plus systemic inflation capture.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </section>

    <div class="disclaimer">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This intrinsic value analysis is an independent study compiled by an AI model (Gemini 2.5 Pro). It is for educational and informational purposes only and does not constitute financial advice, investment recommendations, or an offer to buy or sell securities. Discounted Cash Flow models are highly sensitive to assumptions. Investors should conduct their own due diligence before making investment decisions.
    </div>

  </div>
</SiteLayout>

